content.text:
JSON doesn't support comments, so I can't annotate the files directly. But here's a full explanation of both files and why there are two:

---

## Why two files?

| File | Scope | Purpose |
|------|-------|---------|
| `settings.json` | Global default | Your base config — applies everywhere |
| `settings.local.json` | Local override | Machine/user-specific overrides, not meant to be committed to git |

`settings.local.json` **wins** when both files define the same key. That's what was causing the permission issue — it had a `permissions` block without `bypassPermissions`, silently overriding your global setting.

---

## `settings.json` — annotated

```jsonc
{
  "permissions": {
    // Controls when Claude asks for approval before using tools.
    // "bypassPermissions" = never ask, just do it.
    // Other values: "default" (always ask), "acceptEdits" (auto-approve file edits only)
    "defaultMode": "bypassPermissions"
  },

  "hooks": {
    // Hooks run shell commands automatically on Claude Code events.
    // This one fires every time you submit a prompt.
    "UserPromptSubmit": [{ "hooks": [{ "type": "command", "command": "...session-init", "timeout": 60 }] }],

    // Fires after every tool call (Read, Write, Bash, etc.)
    // Used here by the claude-mem plugin to log observations.
    "PostToolUse": [{ "matcher": "*", "hooks": [{ "type": "command", "command": "...observation", "timeout": 120 }] }],

    // Fires when Claude finishes responding.
    // Used here to auto-summarize the session.
    "Stop": [{ "hooks": [{ "type": "command", "command": "...summarize", "timeout": 120 }] }]
  },

  // Registered plugins active in this installation.
  "enabledPlugins": {
    "claude-mem@thedotmack": true   // persistent memory plugin
  },

  // MCP (Model Context Protocol) servers — external tools Claude can call.
  "mcpServers": {
    "ruflo": {
      "type": "stdio",              // communicates over stdin/stdout
      "command": "node",
      "args": ["/home/nugad/.local/lib/node_modules/ruflo/bin/ruflo.js", "mcp", "start"],
      "env": { "NODE_ENV": "production", "PATH": "..." }
    },
    "claude-mem": {
      "type": "stdio",
      "command": "...mcp-server.cjs"   // claude-mem plugin's MCP server
    }
  },

  // Skips the "you are entering dangerous bypass mode" warning prompt on startup.
  "skipDangerousModePermissionPrompt": true
}
```

---

## `settings.local.json` — annotated

```jsonc
{
  "permissions": {
    // Added by us to fix the override issue — matches global setting.
    "defaultMode": "bypassPermissions",

    // Explicit tool allowlist — these were already allowed before bypassPermissions,
    // but kept here for clarity/legacy reasons.
    "allow": [
      "WebSearch",                     // allows Claude to search the web
      "WebFetch(domain:github.com)"    // allows fetching from github.com specifically
    ]
  }
}
```

---

## The hierarchy in full

If you also have a **project-level** `.claude/settings.json` inside a repo (like `westcoast-marine-parks/.claude/settings.json`), that takes the highest priority for that project only. The load order is:

```
Project .claude/settings.json   ← highest priority (project-specific)
       ↓
~/.claude/settings.local.json   ← machine-local overrides
       ↓
~/.claude/settings.json         ← global defaults (lowest priority)
```
